	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Sik wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You're looking at an average of 12~20 cycles for an opcode with memory access (akin to 6~10 cycles on the 65816 in HiROM).</div><br />I don't see the 65816 being <em>that</em> much faster. Let's look at reading a 16-bit item from an array in an arbitrary bank:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">REP #$30<br />LDA &#91;dd&#93;,Y</div><br />The second instruction takes 7 cycles, or the rough equivalent of 19 cycles on the 68000. (Subtract two if the address points into fast ROM.)<br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Read LDA [dd],Y opcode from fast ROM (2) </li><li>Read direct page address from fast ROM (2) </li><li>Read low byte of address from slow direct page (3) </li><li>Read high byte of address from slow direct page (3) </li><li>Read bank byte of address from slow direct page (3) </li><li>Read low byte of value from slow RAM (3) </li><li>Read high byte of value from slow RAM (3) </li></ol><br />Or from an array in the current data segment (set with PLB):<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">REP #$30<br />LDA (dd),Y</div><br />The second instruction takes 6 cycles, or the equivalent of 16 cycles on the 68000. (Again, subtract two if the address points into fast ROM.)<br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Read LDA [dd],Y opcode from fast ROM (2) </li><li>Read direct page address from fast ROM (2) </li><li>Read low byte of address from slow direct page (3) </li><li>Read high byte of address from slow direct page (3) </li><li>Read low byte of value from slow RAM (3) </li><li>Read high byte of value from slow RAM (3) </li></ol>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


