	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />In the example above 6502 copies byte per iteration while Z80 copies two bytes per iteration, that's why the count is divided by two.<br /><br />Absolute clock frequency does not really matter. It is just a requirement of a particular design. There was a time when 1.79MHz and 3.5MHz were common for 6502 and Z80 respectively, and at the time there was neither 6502 at 3.5MHz nor Z80 at 1.79Mhz. If a common situation would be both CPUs commonly running at the same frequency, then yes, there would be a reason to state that one is faster than another, but it never was like that.<br /><br />Also, I think that it makes sense to judge which is faster and which is 'insanely slow' when you know both CPU very well. If your experience is mostly 6502 and you only read a bit about another CPU, of course you will think 6502 is faster - because you know efficient ways to do things on that CPU and don't know these for another.<br /><br />I would state that both of these two CPUs are more or less equal at their common clock frequencies, with minor advantages and disadvantages in specific areas. I can easily participate in further comprasions.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


